node.text:
Riley and I have always made our best efforts to be self-aware, and to reflect on where we stand as ‘influencers’ on these social media platforms, and on this planet. The mark we leave in the mind’s of our viewers, and on the environment is important to us! I think 2020 has made us realise what’s really important, more than ever.. 

So, what do you guys want to see more of, or less of? Now’s your chance ⛵️🐚🎣🔧👨🏻‍🔬🔮🎸🤿🧘 let us know in the comments. And don’t forget to join us in our latest video on YT. x

Track by @pat.devlin_

node.text:
If you missed our latest video, we share some pretty damn exciting news with you guys.  We are overwhelmed with gratitude that two of our favourite marine companies want to be a part of our project 🥳

Essentially the way we are going to move around the world, with sails and electric propulsion, has been taken care of. This is HUGE. We are one step closer to pulling this off. In fact, maybe two or three steps closer 🥺💙🌎 

@doyle_sails , the most reputable sail makers in the world. Riley has been banging on about these guys for over a year now and he’s obsessed with their cableless sails. 😎😎😎

And @oceanvolt , the leaders in the electric propulsion and regeneration industry. We’re so excited to see what the future looks like for them. 😻

We have each and every one of YOU guys to thank for this. We couldn’t have got here without your support, your comments, emails of advice, years and years of watching our videos and sharing them with your friends. Don’t know what else to say other than we feel like the luckiest people on earth!! It looks like we might just get to build our new dream home on the ocean.. 👨‍👩‍👦⛵️✨ #sailinglavagabonde #doylesails #oceanvolt

node.text: Because, are you even really on an adventure if you’re not in a Kombi? 😅 @kombicamping_ . We’ve had some fun lately. I didn’t think I’d be feeling up for any kind of travel for some time after having Darwin.. but 2 weeks postpartum I went for my first run. Another week later, we went on a road trip to go and dive a sinkhole. I don’t know how or why I feel this good, but I feel very lucky and I’m just rolling with it 😌

It takes about 3.5 hours to do a full lap of Uluru.. the perfect walk if you ask me. Did you know it’s also taller than the Eiffel Tower? 

The Uluru-Kata Tjuta region has been home to the Anangu people for more than 30 000 years. It felt pretty special to be walking on such wild and sacred country.

More Australian adventures will be rolling in soon over on our channel, link is in my bio 🏜🌊

node.text:
Another cracking day in our suburban Aussie backyard. It’s hilarious that you all spotted the ‘Aussie clothesline’ in an old photo I posted and knew we were in Australia before we’d announced it over on YouTube hahaha. 🕵🏽‍♂️
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It's been an emotional time lately with reunions, the birth and all of my pregnancy hormones.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Most mornings I would make a coffee and come sit out the back, look at the garden, and just appreciate our little yard. It was nice having the space to prepare my mind, body and home for Darwin to arrive. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
We've been living here at this Air BnB for the last couple of months, however we'll be saying goodbye very soon.. and there’s one more stop before we hit Vietnam (we’re stopping by West Oz to visit my friends and family). 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Join us for some hangs in the suburbs and to see what we get up to when the boat's not around. Channel link is in my bio if you've missed this one. xo
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
#sailinglavagabonde
